      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the confusion earlier! You are absolutely right to ask for a clearer explanation without the goblin metaphors.\n\nTo answer your specific question: **Yes, a Durable Power of Attorney (DPOA) is specifically designed to protect your dad's house and bank accounts if he gets dementia.**\n\nHere is the breakdown of how it works legally:\n\n1.  **The \"Durable\" Part:** A standard Power of Attorney usually ends immediately if the person signing it becomes incapacitated. A **Durable** Power of Attorney includes language stating that the authority granted to you (the agent) continues even if your dad loses the mental capacity to make decisions himself.\n2.  **Scope of Protection:** When you draft this document, you can specify exactly what powers you have. You can explicitly grant yourself the authority to:\n    *   Manage bank accounts and pay bills.\n    *   Sell, buy, or manage real estate (his house).\n    *   File taxes.\n    *   Handle medical decisions (though this often requires a separate \"Healthcare Proxy\" document, it can be included in the same package).\n3.  **Why it matters for Dementia:** If your dad gets",
